Ways to connect to a remote repo

Git clone
1-git clone <remote-url>

Examples:

HTTPS â†’ git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git

SSH â†’ git clone git@github.com:user/repo.git

GitHub CLI â†’ gh repo clone user/repo

2= Add a Remote to an Existing Local Repo

git remote add origin <remote-url>


Examples:

HTTPS â†’ git remote add origin https://github.com/user/repo.git

SSH â†’ git remote add origin git@github.com:user/repo.git

3- Fork + Clone (Special GitHub / GitLab flow)

Fork a repo on GitHub/GitLab.

Clone your fork:

git clone https://github.com/your-username/repo.git


Add the original repo as upstream:

git remote add upstream https://github.com/original-owner/repo.git

4 - Generate an SSH Key (if not already)

ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"


Default location:

Private key â†’ ~/.ssh/id_rsa

Public key â†’ ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

Add SSH Key to Agent

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa


Copy Public Key to Remote Hosting Service

cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub


Copy the output and paste into:

GitHub â†’ Settings > SSH and GPG Keys > New SSH Key

GitLab â†’ Settings > SSH Keys

Bitbucket â†’ Personal Settings > SSH Keys

                        
